{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17525208","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17525208"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:13:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:13:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14066"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14066","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14066"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.31,0.46,0.09,0.07,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6725"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53628"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6725","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6725"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14066"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39088"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1086"},{"type":"tags","id":"1864"},{"type":"tags","id":"3620"},{"type":"tags","id":"6610"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"14267"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53628","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53628"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-week history of progressive bilateral leg swelling. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 78/min, blood pressure 158/88 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. There is pitting oedema to both knees. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrinalysis shows 3+ protein. Investigations reveal serum albumin 28 g/L (35-50), total cholesterol 7.2 mmol/L (2.0-5.0), and urine protein-to-creatinine ratio of 560 mg/mmol (\u0026lt;15). The patient undergoes a renal biopsy, where light microscopy demonstrates a thickened basement membrane, and there is diffuse granular glomerular basement membrane staining on immunofluorescence.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations is most useful in differentiating between the primary and secondary cause of this disease?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Complement C3 and C4 levels","Phospholipase A2 receptor (PLA2R) antibody","Urine albumin-creatinine ratio","Beta-2 glycoprotein antibody","Urine microscopy for cast analysis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features of nephrotic syndrome (oedema, hypoalbuminaemia, hypercholesterolaemia, and proteinuria) and has biopsy findings consistent with membranous nephropathy. The key question is how to differentiate between primary (idiopathic) and secondary membranous nephropathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhospholipase A2 receptor (PLA2R) antibody\u003C/strong\u003E testing is the most useful investigation for this purpose. PLA2R antibodies are highly specific (\u0026gt;95%) for primary membranous nephropathy and are present in about 70-80% of patients with this condition. The presence of these antibodies strongly suggests primary membranous nephropathy, while their absence points towards a secondary cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplement C3 and C4 levels\u003C/strong\u003E are not specific for membranous nephropathy. While they may be low in some secondary causes (e.g., lupus nephritis), they are not helpful in differentiating primary and secondary causes as definitively as PLA2R testing. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrine albumin-creatinine ratio\u003C/strong\u003E is a measure of albuminuria (similar to urine protein-creatinine ratio but only for albumin), which would be expected to be elevated given the high UPCR. Whilst this test is useful for quantifying proteinuria, it does not help differentiate between primary and secondary causes of membranous nephropathy. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBeta-2 glycoprotein antibody\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with antiphospholipid syndrome. It is not helpful in differentiating primary and secondary causes of membranous nephropathy.  \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrine microscopy for cast analysis\u003C/strong\u003E can provide information about kidney damage but doesn\u0027t specifically differentiate between primary and secondary membranous nephropathy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["PLA2R antibodies are highly specific for primary membranous nephropathy.","Nephrotic syndrome is a common presentation of membranous nephropathy."],"references":["Beck LH, Bonegio RGB, Lambeau G, Beck DM, Powell DW, Cummins TD, et al. M-Type Phospholipase A2Receptor as Target Antigen in Idiopathic Membranous Nephropathy. New England Journal of Medicine. 2009 Jul 2;361(1):11\u201321. Available at: https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMoa0810457"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39088"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14066"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39088","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39088"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-23T14:08:29+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-23T14:10:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6725"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53628"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"]